06532nam a22012975i 9781400851737DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222008nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008517377 a10.1515/97814008517372doi  a(DE-B1597)613593  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aBR856b.H476 2008eb 7aREL0670802bisacsh04a274.3/08232221 aHeschel, Susannah, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Aryan Jesus :bChristian Theologians and the Bible in Nazi Germany /cSusannah Heschel. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2022] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (384 p.) :b30 halftones.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tA Note on Archival Sources -- tAcknowledgments -- tList of Abbreviations -- tIntroduction. Theology and Race -- tChapter I. Draining Jesus of Jewishness -- tChapter II. The Institute for the Study and Eradication of Jewish Influence on German Church Life, 1939 to 1942 -- tChapter III. Projects of the Institute -- tChapter IV. The Making of Nazi Theologians -- tChapter V. The Faculty of Theology at the University of Jena -- tChapter VI. The Postwar Years -- tConclusion. Crucified or Resurrected: Institute Theology in Postwar Germany -- tBibliography -- tIllustration Permissions -- tIndex -- tScriptural Citations Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWas Jesus a Nazi? During the Third Reich, German Protestant theologians, motivated by racism and tapping into traditional Christian anti-Semitism, redefined Jesus as an Aryan and Christianity as a religion at war with Judaism. In 1939, these theologians established the Institute for the Study and Eradication of Jewish Influence on German Religious Life. In The Aryan Jesus, Susannah Heschel shows that during the Third Reich, the Institute became the most important propaganda organ of German Protestantism, exerting a widespread influence and producing a nazified Christianity that placed anti-Semitism at its theological center. Based on years of archival research, The Aryan Jesus examines the membership and activities of this controversial theological organization. With headquarters in Eisenach, the Institute sponsored propaganda conferences throughout the Nazi Reich and published books defaming Judaism, including a dejudaized version of the New Testament and a catechism proclaiming Jesus as the savior of the Aryans. Institute members--professors of theology, bishops, and pastors--viewed their efforts as a vital support for Hitler's war against the Jews. Heschel looks in particular at Walter Grundmann, the Institute's director and a professor of the New Testament at the University of Jena. Grundmann and his colleagues formed a community of like-minded Nazi Christians who remained active and continued to support each other in Germany's postwar years. The Aryan Jesus raises vital questions about Christianity's recent past and the ambivalent place of Judaism in Christian thought.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aChurch and statezGermanyxHistoryy1933-1945. 0aGerman-Christian movement. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)xCauses. 0aJudaism (Christian theology)xHistory of doctrinesy20th century. 0aNational socialism and religion. 0aProtestant churcheszGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 7aRELIGION / Christian Theology / History.2bisacsh  aAbel, Wolfgang.  aAltenburg, church in.  aAngelos.  aArische Rundschau.  aAssyriology.  aAugsburg Confession.  aBabylonian mythology.  aBarmen Declaration (1934).  aBayreuth Blätter.  aBirnbaum, Walter.  aBuchenwald concentration camp.  aCall of Life.  aCatholicism.  aConti, Leonardo.  aDalman, Gustav.